ogical theories. This collected volume explores how ethnographies of indigenous South America have helped to inspire this analytic shift, demonstrating the continued importance of ethnographic diversity. Most importantly, this volume asserts that comparative ethnographic research can help illustrate complex questions surrounding relations vis-à-vis the homogenizing effects of modern coloniality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aEthnologyzSouth America. 0aIndians of South AmericaxKinship. 0aIndians of South AmericaxSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBacchiddu, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBacchiddu, Giovanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBonelli, Cristóbal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Giminiani, Piergiorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiminiani, Piergiorgio Di, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGonzález Gálvez, Marcelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGálvez, Marcelo González, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLagrou, Els, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillacura Salas, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPazzarelli, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrathern, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTola, Florencia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVanzolini, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVilaça, Aparecida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c